<exercisegroup xml:id="eg-derivApp-motion-tf">
  <title>True/False Questions</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Determine whether each statement is true or false.
      Justify your answers.
    </p>
  </introduction>


  <exercise xml:id="ex-derivApp-motion-tf-12">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>v(t)=s'(t)</m> is positive on <m>(a,b)</m>, then <m>s(t)</m> is increasing on <m>(a,b)</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <em>True.</em>
        If the velocity is positive, the position function is increasing.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>



  <exercise xml:id="ex-derivApp-motion-tf-14">
    <statement>
      <p>
        For <m>s(t)=-5t^2+15t+6</m>, the ball reaches its maximum height at <m>t=2</m> seconds because <m>v(2)=0</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <em>False.</em>
        The velocity function is <m>v(t)=s'(t)=-10t+15</m>.
        Setting <m>v(t)=0</m>, we solve:
        <me>
0 = -10t + 15 \Rightarrow t = 1.5.
        </me>
        Therefore, the ball reaches its maximum height at <m>t=1.5</m> seconds, not <m>t=2</m> seconds.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>


  <exercise xml:id="ex-derivApp-motion-tf-03">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>v(t)=0</m> at a time <m>t=5</m>, then the object must change direction at <m>t=5</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <em>False.</em>
        When the velocity is zero, the object is momentarily at rest.
        However, this does not necessarily mean that the object changes direction at that time.
        For example, if the velocity changes from positive to zero and then back to positive, the object does not change direction.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  
  <exercise xml:id="ex-derivApp-motion-tf-08">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>v(t)</m> is decreasing on an interval, then the object is slowing down on that interval.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <em>False.</em>
        If the velocity is decreasing, it means that the acceleration is negative.
        However, whether the object is slowing down or speeding up depends on the sign of the velocity as well.
        If the velocity is positive and decreasing, the object is slowing down.
        But if the velocity is negative and decreasing, the object is actually speeding up.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-derivApp-motion-tf-06">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>a(t)=0</m> at a time <m>t=3</m>, then the object must be at rest (even momentarily) at <m>t=3</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <em>False.</em>
        When the acceleration is zero, it means that the velocity is not changing at that time.
        However, this does not necessarily mean that the object is at rest.
        The object could be moving with a constant velocity.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-derivApp-motion-tf-04">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>v(6)&gt;0</m> and <m>a(6)&gt;0</m>, then the object is speeding up at <m>t=6</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <em>True.</em>
        Since the velocity is positive, the object is moving in the positive direction.
        Since the acceleration is also positive, the velocity is increasing.
        Therefore, the speed of the object is increasing, which means the object is speeding up.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>








  <exercise xml:id="ex-derivApp-motion-tf-10">
    <statement>
      <p>
        The total distance traveled on <m>[a,b]</m> is always greater than or equal to <m>|s(b)-s(a)|</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <em>True.</em>
        The total distance traveled accounts for all movement, regardless of direction, while <m>|s(b)-s(a)|</m> only measures the net change in position.
        Therefore, the total distance traveled is always greater than or equal to the absolute value of the displacement.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-derivApp-motion-tf-11">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If an object never changes direction on <m>[a,b]</m>, then its total distance traveled equals <m>|s(b)-s(a)|</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <em>True.</em>
        If the object never changes direction, it means that it is either always moving in the positive direction or always moving in the negative direction.
        In either case, the total distance traveled is equal to the absolute value of the displacement, which is <m>|s(b)-s(a)|</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

<exercise xml:id="ex-derivApp-motion-tf-102">
    <statement>
      <p>
        An object moving along a line has position function <m>s(t)=t^3-6t^2+9t</m>.
        The object is speeding up on the interval <m>(0,3)</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <em>False.</em>
        First, we find the velocity and acceleration functions:
        <me>
v(t) = s'(t) = 3t^2 - 12t + 9,
        </me>
        <me>
a(t) = v'(t) = 6t - 12.
        </me>
        Next, we determine the signs of velocity and acceleration on the interval <m>(0,3)</m>.
        Setting <m>v(t)=0</m>, we solve:
        <me>
0 = 3t^2 - 12t + 9 \Rightarrow t^2 - 4t + 3 = 0 \Rightarrow (t-1)(t-3) = 0 \Rightarrow t = 1, 3.
        </me>
        Thus, on the interval <m>(0,3)</m>, the velocity is positive on <m>(0,1)</m> and negative on <m>(1,3)</m>.
        Setting <m>a(t)=0</m>, we solve:
        <me>
0 = 6t - 12 \Rightarrow t = 2.
        </me>
        Thus, on the interval <m>(0,3)</m>, the acceleration is negative on <m>(0,2)</m> and positive on <m>(2,3)</m>.
        Therefore, the object is slowing down on <m>(0,1)</m> and <m>(1,2)</m>, and speeding up on <m>(2,3)</m>.
        Since the object is not speeding up on the entire interval <m>(0,3)</m>, the statement is false.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>


